column3: Description

Defines what type of update will be done when loading the file.
If Value field equals 0, only the values from field Value will be updated >= 100.
If Value field equals 1, values (all values from all fields) will be updated.
If Value field equals 2, values  (value, default, factory) will be updated >= 100.
If Value field equals 3, values (value, default) will be updated.
If Value field equals 4, values (value, default) will be updated >= 100.
If Value field equals 5, Hourmeters + Modules will be updated.
A High-Level code will be asked when loading the file if Value field = 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5 If no valid code is inserted, a standard update will be done.
Default field has a coded time window value. Only updates done inside that time window will be executed.
Factory field will keep the info of initial programming of parameters. If a value of 1 is present, parameters have been loaded into the machine. If it has a different value, parameters (full version) has to be loaded.
MIN field will keep the info about dispatch procedures. If value is different from 1, means that dispatch procedures were not made yet.

Defines what is the model/variant of the truck.
The only field that has valid info is Factory. This field can only be updated with High-Level Access Code.

The Factory field also defines if the truck uses Curtis F-Series controllers
0=SE only
1=F-Series (Traction and Pump)
2= All F-Series(Traction, Pump and Steer)
This field can only be updated with High-Level Access Code.

Defines what is the Serial Number of the truck in Factory field.
This field can only be updated with High-Level Access Code.
The Min field keeps the truck Chassis Length value.
The Max field keeps the truck Chassis Width value.

Defines the date when the truck was built (dispatch procedures done). 
This field can only be updated with High-Level Access Code.

Field Factory: Factory build date (Epoch)
Field Min: Dealer installation date (Epoch)
Field Max: Customer installation date (Epoch)

Defines the version of the CLP API present in the truck.
The only field that has valid info is Factory. This field can only be updated with High-Level Access Code
Field Factory: Defines the version of the CLP API present in the truck.
Field Min: show serial/ date visu after load new parameters (BOOL only used before dispatch)

Defines how Driver Presence Mode will work. Info is stored at bit level.
0 – Off  1 – On

bit 0 - Seat (Cannot Change)
bit 1 - Seatbelt
bit 2 - Operator enable
bit 3 - free
bit 4 - free
bit 5 - Sequence
bit 6 - Sequence at start
bit 7 - Hydraulics

Seat – Operator must be in the seat (floor) to validate Driver Presence Mode.
Seatbelt – Operator must have the seatbelt fastened (door) to validate Driver Presence Mode.
Operator enable – Operator must have this input enabled to validate Driver Presence Mode.
Sequence – Seatbelt input can only be activated after seat input to validate Driver Presence Mode.
Sequence at start – if Off, on the first check after keyswitch it will test if both seat and seatbelt are active to validate Driver Presence Mode not checking for sequence.
Hydraulics – If On, allows to use the hydraulic functions from the truck checking only if seat input is active.
Defines the time delay for Seat input action.
Defines the time delay for Seatbelt input action.
The current applied to the hydraulic coils when not being used.
The PWM applied to the hydraulic coils when not being used.

Defines how Work Lights will work. Info is stored at bit level.

Carousel – Lights will turn On when Active Drive Mode is Carousel.
Crab – Lights will turn On when Active Drive Mode is Crab.
Start – Lights will turn On (selected mode) on ksw On.

Defines how Motion Alarm will work. Info is stored at bit level.
0 – Off  1 – On

bit 0 - Forks
bit 1 - Reverse of Forks
bit 2 - Left of Forks
bit 3 - Right of Forks
bit 4 - Offset
bit 5 - Carousel or Crab
bit 6 - Hydraulics
bit 7 - Lower

Forks – Motion Alarm On when Active Drive Mode is Forks direction.
Rev Forks – Motion Alarm On when Active Drive Mode is Reverse Forks direction.
Left of Forks – Motion Alarm On when Active Drive Mode is Left of Forks direction.
Right of Forks – Motion Alarm On when Active Drive Mode is Right of Forks direction.
Offset – Motion Alarm On when Offset Mode is active.
Carousel or Crab – Motion Alarm On when Carousel or Crab Mode is active.
Hydraulics – Motion Alarm On when any hydraulic function is active.
Lower – Motion Alarm On when any hydraulic function Lower is active.

Defines what mode is set as default for Motion Alarm.
0 – Motion Alarm Off

LSB defines the Hydraulic Function that will be used in Function 1.
Codes for each hydraulic function are available in Appendix F
Bit 0-7 Records the Hydraulic Function code. 
Bits 8 to 13 are used to setup the 3 supported 6-ports for that function.

Bit 9 OFF – 6 port 1 not required
Bit 9 OFF AND  Bit 8 OFF – 6 port 1 required and must be OFF
Bit 9 OFF AND  Bit 8 ON – 6 port 1 required and must be ON
Bit 11 OFF – 6 port 2 not required
Bit 11 OFF AND  Bit 10 OFF – 6 port 2 required and must be OFF
Bit 11 OFF AND  Bit 10 ON – 6 port 2 required and must be ON
Bit 13 OFF – 6 port 3 not required
Bit 13 OFF AND  Bit 12 OFF – 6 port 3 required and must be OFF
Bit 13 OFF AND  Bit 12 ON – 6 port 3 required and must be ON

Defines hydraulic 1 input configuration. Info is stored at bit level.

Each bit has different functions depending on the type of input selected.

There are 4 types of input available, configured with bit 0 and 1.
Bit 0 OFF AND  Bit 1 OFF – No feedback (levers)
Bit 0 ON AND  Bit 1 OFF – Switches feedback
Bit 0 OFF AND  Bit 1 ON – Joystick
Bit 0 ON AND  Bit 1 ON – Fingertips

If input type is set as ‘No feedback’, bits 2 to 15 are not used.
If input type is set as ‘Switches’, bits 2 to 9 are used to identify the switch input allocated to the function. Bits 10 to 15 are not used.
Bit 2 – 1A
Bit 3 – 2A
Bit 4 – 3A
Bit 5 – 4A
Bit 6 – 1B
Bit 7 – 2B
Bit 8 – 3B
Bit 9 – 4B

If input type is set as ‘Joystick’, bits 2 to 3 are used to identify the joystick axis direction allocated to the function. Bits 4 to 9 are not used. Bits 10 to 15 are used to assign buttons to the function.
Bit 2 – Y axis
Bit 3 – X axis
Bit 10 – 1
Bit 11 – 2
Bit 12 – 3
Bit 13 – 4
Bit 14 – 5
Bit 15 – 6

If input type is set as ‘Fingertip’, bits 2 to 7 are used to identify the fingertip allocated to the function. Bits 8 to 15 are not used.
Bit 2 – A
Bit 3 – B
Bit 4 – C
Bit 5 – D
Bit 6 – E
Bit 7 – F

Defines hydraulic 1 output configuration. Info is stored at bit level.
0 – Off  1 – On
Bits 2 to 7 have different functions depending on the type of output selected.
There are 3 types of output available, configured with bit 0 and 1. 
Bit 0 OFF AND  Bit 1 OFF – No output
Bit 0 ON AND  Bit 1 OFF – PWM On/Off
Bit 0 OFF AND  Bit 1 ON – PWM Proportional
Bit 0 ON AND  Bit 1 ON – PVG

If output type is set as ‘No output’, bits 2 to 15 are not used.

If output type is set as ‘PWM On/Off’ or ‘PWM Proportional’, bits 2 to 5 are used to identify the section of the valvebank allocated to the function. Bits 6 and 7 not used.
Bit 2 – 1
Bit 3 – 2
Bit 4 – 3
Bit 5 – 4

If output type is set as ‘PVG’, bits 2 to 7 are used to identify the PVG output allocated to the function. 
Bit 2 – 1
Bit 3 – 2
Bit 4 – 3
Bit 5 – 4
Bit 6 – 5
Bit 7 – 6

Bit 8 is used to set priority when requested speed from the function is lower than the other active functions.

Bits 9 and 10 are free.

Bits 11 and 12 are used to setup the redundancy type of the input used in that function. These settings depend on the hardware used in the truck.
Bit 11 OFF AND  Bit 12 OFF – Channel 1
Bit 11 ON AND  Bit 12 OFF – Channel 2
Bit 11 OFF AND  Bit 12 ON – Channel 1 + Channel 2
Bit 11 ON AND  Bit 12 ON – Channel 1 + Switch

Bit 13, ‘Feedback’, is used to setup the type of feedback available from that output.
0 – No feedback  1 – Current Feedback

Bit 14, ‘Invert’, is used to setup the flow direction of that output.
0 – Default Direction  1 – Invert Direction

Bit 15, ‘Return to Neutral’, is used to setup if input command must return to neutral when multiple functions are active simultaneously.
0 – No Return to Neutral 1 – Return to Neutral needed

Bit 11 OFF AND  Bit 12 ON – Channel 1 + Channel 2
Bit 11 ON AND  Bit 12 ON – Channel 1 + Switch

Bit 13, ‘Feedback’, is used to setup the type of feedback available from that output.
0 – No feedback  1 – Current Feedback

Bit 14, ‘Invert’, is used to setup the flow direction of that output.
0 – Default Direction  1 – Invert Direction

Bit 15, ‘Return to Neutral’, is used to setup if input command must return to neutral when multiple functions are active simultaneously.
0 – No Return to Neutral 1 – Return to Neutral needed

.4 Right - Disable/Enable the use of OSCam1 when driving in Right of Forks direction.

Defines the type of brake used in the truck. Available types are:
1- Connected to TRR, 2-wire rheostat, 5 kΩ–0 input
2- Connected to TRR, single-ended 3-wire 1 kΩ–10 kΩ potentiometer, or 0–5 V voltage source
3- Connected to TRR, 2-wire rheostat, 0–5 kΩ input
4- Not available
5- CAN
If Brake Type = 5 (CAN), the ID identifies what device is used in the truck. Brake Device ID’s are available in Appendix K

Defines how Height Assist will work. Info is stored at bit level.
0 – Off  1 – On

Bit 2 – free

Bit 4 – Speed – If TRUE, use Height Assist Stop Speed rpm. If FALSE, use Height Assist Stop Speed val
Bit 5 – Zone A – If TRUE, Zone A is enabled
Bit 6 – Zone B – If TRUE, Zone B is enabled
Bit 7 – Zone C – If TRUE, Zone C is enabled
Bit 8 – Travel Pos – If TRUE, use the Travel position setting to stop lift or lower
Bit 9 – Load Pos – If TRUE, use the Load position setting to stop lift or lower
Bit 10 – Platform Pos – If TRUE, use the Platform position setting to stop lift or lower

Allignment type to be used in CINAS
Centre - Aisle must be detected in both sides (front and rear of the machine). 
Front - Aisle only needs to be detected in the front of the machine. 
Rear - Aisle only needs to be detected in the rear of the machine.

Enter Aisle Mode to be used in CINAS
All Sensors ON - All the configured sensors need to be detecting the aisle to change mode into Aisle Mode.
Leading Sensors ON - Only the configured leading sensors need to be detecting the aisle to change mode into Aisle Mode.

Exit Aisle Mode to be used in CINAS
All Sensors OFF - All the configured sensors need to be cleared to exit from Aisle Mode. 
Leading Sensors OFF - Only the configured leading sensors need to be cleared to exit from Aisle Mode. 
Any Leading Sensor OFF - Any of the configured leading sensors when cleared will exit Aisle Mode.

Defines some battery options. Stored at bit level.

bit0 --> Battery Charging plug. (0 – switch is normally CLOSED to operate,  1 –  switch is Normally OPEN to operate)
bit1 --> Battery in Place Switch.  (0 – switch is normally CLOSED to operate,  1 –  switch is Normally OPEN to operate)
